'''Hayashi Shrine''' (林神社) is a {{ill|Shinto shrine|ja|神社|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shinto shrine|qq=}} located in {{ill|Miyanoue|ja|宮の上|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Miyanoue|qq=}}, {{ill|Akashi City|ja|明石市|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Akashi City|qq=}}, {{ill|Hyōgo Prefecture|ja|兵庫県|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Hyōgo Prefecture|qq=}}, Japan. The shrine is historically associated with the origin of the name "Akashi" and is notable for its autumn festival featuring a single {{ill|Futondaiko (decorated drum float)|ja|布団太鼓|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Futondaiko (decorated drum float)|qq=}}.

== Enshrined Deities ==
The shrine's main deity is {{ill|Watatsumi|ja|少童海命|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Watatsumi|qq=}}. Other enshrined deities include:
* {{ill|Hikohohodemi no Mikoto|ja|彦火火出見命|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Hikohohodemi no Mikoto|qq=}}
* {{ill|Toyotama-hime|ja|豊玉姫命|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Toyotama-hime|qq=}}
* {{ill|Ugaya Fukiaezu no Mikoto|ja|鸕鷀草葺不合尊|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ugaya Fukiaezu no Mikoto|qq=}}
* {{ill|Tamayorihime|ja|タマヨリビメ (日向神話)|1=Tamayori-hime (mother of Jimmu)|lt=Tamayori-hime|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tamayorihime|13=User:Immanuelle/Tamayori-hime (mother of Jimmu)|qq=}}
* Misaki-no-Okami (御崎大神)

== History ==
According to legend, the shrine was established during the 9th year of {{ill|Seimu Emperor|ja|成務天皇|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Seimu Emperor|qq=}}, when {{ill|Watatsumi|ja|少童海命|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Watatsumi|qq=}} manifested on a large red rock on the seashore. The red rock later sank into the sea due to waves in the 8th year, leading to the shrine’s construction on a hill to oversee maritime safety. It is considered the oldest shrine in {{ill|Akashi City|ja|明石市|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Akashi City|qq=}}.<ref name="神社庁">[http://www.hyogo-jinjacho.com/data/6309016.html 林神社], Hyōgo Prefecture Shrine Association, accessed February 4, 2024.</ref>

The shrine was listed as "Hayashi Shrine" in the {{ill|Engishiki Jinmyōchō|1=Engishiki Jinmyōchō|2=ja|3=延喜式神名帳|4=zh|5=延喜式神名帳|6=simple|7=Engishiki Jinmyocho|ja|延喜式神名帳|1=Engishiki Jinmyōchō|1=Engishiki Jinmyōchō|2=ja|3=延喜式神名帳|4=zh|5=延喜式神名帳|6=simple|7=Engishiki Jinmyōchō|1=Engishiki Jinmyōchō|2=ja|3=延喜式神名帳|4=zh|5=延喜式神名帳|6=simple|7=Engishiki Jinmyocho|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Engishiki Jinmyōchō|13=User:Immanuelle/Engishiki Jinmyōchō|qq=}}, compiled in the 5th year of {{ill|Enchō (era)|ja|延長|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Enchō (era)|qq=}} (927 CE), as a minor shrine of {{ill|Harima Province|ja|播磨国|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Harima Province|qq=}}, Akashi District.

In the 2nd year of {{ill|Kankō (era)|ja|寛弘|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kankō (era)|qq=}} (1005 CE), four additional deities were enshrined, and the shrine was subsequently known as "Uemiya Gosha Daimyōjin" (上宮五社大明神).<ref name="神社庁" />

During the {{ill|Meiji era|ja|明治時代|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Meiji era|qq=}}, the shrine merged with the nearby shrine of Misaki-no-Okami. It was designated a prefectural shrine (県社) in Meiji 14 (1881).

== Access ==
* Rail: Approximately a 5-minute walk from {{ill|Hayashizaki Matsuekaigan Station|ja|林崎松江海岸駅|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Hayashizaki Matsuekaigan Station|qq=}} on the {{ill|Sanyo Electric Railway|ja|山陽電気鉄道|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Sanyo Electric Railway|qq=}} Main Line.

